    <td>
      <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
        <tr>
          <td>
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2">
              <tr> 
                <td class="chblue"><font class="h1font">Beginner Decks</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3"><tr><td><font class="bfont"><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0"><tr><td colspan="2"><font class="h1font">Arderian Aerial Atheletes</font></td></tr><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Rating</Font></TD><TD><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size=1>(4.10)</font> | <A HREF="/magination/decks/decks.php?reviews=20967">Read Reviews</A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Author</font></TD><TD><font class="bfont"> <A HREF="http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=9014">Ryan "Pisces6996" Mitchell</A></FONT> <font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=9014&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a></font></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Description</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> An Arderial deck that introduces the beginner to the Moonlands&#39; jack-of-all-trades!</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Submitted</Font></TD><TD><font class="bfont"> January 29, 2002</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Cards</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> MAGI:<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(526)">Aula</a> (Starting: <a href="javascript:card_browser(519)">Brannix</a>, <a href="javascript:card_browser(521)">J&#39;lith</a>, <a href="javascript:card_browser(348)">Cloud Sceptre</a>)<br>
<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(344)">Ora</a> (Starting: <a href="javascript:card_browser(339}<a href="javascript:card_browser({337)">Xyx</a> Minor</a>, <a href="javascript:card_browser(338}<a href="javascript:card_browser({337)">Xyx</a> Elder</a>, <a href="javascript:card_browser(356)">Shooting Star</a>)<br>
<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(528)">Sorreah</a> (Starting: <a href="javascript:card_browser(670}<a href="javascript:card_browser({528)">Sorreah</a>&#39;s Dream</a>, Any 2 Arderial Spells)<br>
<br>
CREATURES: 21 total<br>
3 <a href="javascript:card_browser(339}<a href="javascript:card_browser({337)">Xyx</a> Minor</a><br>
3 <a href="javascript:card_browser(337)">Xyx</a><br>
3 <a href="javascript:card_browser(338}<a href="javascript:card_browser({337)">Xyx</a> Elder</a><br>
3 <a href="javascript:card_browser(520)">Flutter Yup</a><br>
2 <a href="javascript:card_browser(324)">Alaban</a><br>
2 <a href="javascript:card_browser(326)">Cloud Narth</a><br>
2 <a href="javascript:card_browser(333)">Pharan</a><br>
1 <a href="javascript:card_browser(519)">Brannix</a><br>
1 <a href="javascript:card_browser(521)">J&#39;lith</a><br>
1 <a href="javascript:card_browser(585)">Dark <a href="javascript:card_browser(325)">Ayebaw</a></a><br>
<br>
SPELLS: 12 total<br>
3 <a href="javascript:card_browser(355)">Shockwave</a><br>
3 <a href="javascript:card_browser(670}<a href="javascript:card_browser({528)">Sorreah</a>&#39;s Dream</a><br>
3 <a href="javascript:card_browser(354)">Lightning</a><br>
2 <a href="javascript:card_browser(669)">Cataclysm</a><br>
1 <a href="javascript:card_browser(356)">Shooting Star</a><br>
<br>
RELICS: 7 total<br>
3 <a href="javascript:card_browser(512)">Warrior&#39;s Boots</a><br>
2 Arderian Guard Wings<br>
2 <a href="javascript:card_browser(348)">Cloud Sceptre</a>  </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> AULA:<br>
Our first athelete is Aula, who allows us to establish control of the board early and provides the following magi with a nice size hand as well.<br>
Your strategy will differ depending on whether you choose to go first or second...<br>
<br>
1st turn going first:  Remove her 3 starters and draw 2 more to bring her hand to 5.  Next, play her Cloud Sceptre as well as the J&#39;lith and the Brannix.  (Always remember to play the Cloud Sceptre before playing the J&#39;lith, because if you play the J&#39;lith w/o having a relic in play, its coveting effect will trigger, and you will have to discard it!)  The J&#39;lith will gain 2 energy if your opponent plays a relic, making them think twice about playing one to begin w/...and if it sticks around until your next turn, you can pump it up by playing a relic of your own.  The Brannix will gain an energy when attacking and gain 3 should it attack an Arderial creature!  Regardless of what else you drew, you should use her Windsight power to discard them and bring your hand to 5 again.  However, should you draw something really useful such as a Shockwave in your opening hand, your Brannix is now expendable.  With a little bit of practice, you will begin to understand what you need to hold on to and what is expendable, but using her Windsight power to build your hand is your top priority.<br>
<br>
1st turn going second:  Here is where you build your experience by taking a good look at the playing field and sizing it up to decide if pulling all of her starting cards would be as beneficial as say, pulling only her Cloud Sceptre and drawing the other 4 cards to possibly increase your chances of drawing a Shockwave, Cataclysm, Xyx Elder, or Alaban to remove any potential threats.  What happens if you don&#39;t draw any of these...?  In emergencies, simply pay 1 energy to discard as many cards as you wish with the Cloud Sceptre&#39;s Mindwinds power and try again!  <br>
This type of judgement will come with experience but it will improve your game tremendously over time!  It&#39;s these kind of options that have made Arderial a favorite among players and earned them the title of jack-of-all-trades.<br>
<br>
A common downside to playing w/ Aula is a tendency to get a little carried away w/ discarding cards to cycle through your deck.  Often times you will discard important cards in hopes of drawing what you want...only to curse yourself later on for not holding on to them.  In order to avoid this, of course you will need practice, but for now, as a general rule try not to discard Xyx Minors, Shockwaves, or Cataclysms.  The Minors are very essential to Ora&#39;s effectiveness and the latter are always of use.  Continue to play smart w/ Aula, playing Flutter Yups and pumping them up w/ Lightning, Cloud Narths and Pharans.  Feel free to play a Xyx Minor if you can pump it up right away, but if possible, try and hold on to them for Ora.  Try to get the Arderian Guard Wings into play early to protect your creatures from devastating Thunderquakes and pesky Cald burn tactics.  Continue cycling cards to keep your hand sizable and Aula should provide a tough fight for anyone.<br>
<br>
ORA:<br>
Our second magi and star athelete is Ora.  When you reveal Ora, pull her 3 starters (remember: discard pile 1st) and proceed to play all of your Xyx Minors as well as a Xyx and a Xyx Elder.  Since Ora&#39;s Strengthen effect gives all of your creatures an additional energy when played, your Xyx Minors can now use their Gathering Clouds powers on each other and even themselves w/o dying in the process!  Use the Xyx Elder&#39;s Shockstorm power remove a die roll of energy from all non-xyx creatures in play.  And to further cripple them, use the Xyx&#39;s Shock power to remove 4 energy from their magi.  Another invaluable strategy in this situation is to use Sorreah&#39;s Dream to copy any of the Xyx powers for double the impact!  For 2 energy you can copy Gathering Clouds to add 4 energy to any of the Xyx, for 6 you can copy Shockstorm to make amends for a bad roll or finish anything fortunate enough to have survived, and for 3 you can copy Shock and remove 4 additional energy from their magi!  With this kind of power who needs to attack, right!?:)  However, should the opposing forces be too large for the Elder to takcle...a Cataclysm is just as devastating if not more so, being that it will discard all of their relics as well.  You may lose any Warriors Boots you have in your hand if you do, so use your better judgement to decide which will benefit you more.  Once you gain control of the board, try to keep your opponent relatively weak and helpless before killing them...allowing Ora to build a remarkable army capable of killing their following magi w/ ease.  It&#39;s the &quot;first rule of duel&quot; which you can read about in the article section of this very site.<br>
<br>
SORREAH:<br>
Our final athelete is Sorreah who specializes in cleaning house!  When you reveal Sorreah, you will first check your discard pile for a copy of Sorreah&#39;s Dream as well as 2 other Arderial spells of your choice.  If by chance, there are no Sorreah&#39;s Dream in the discard, you may then search your deck for a copy.  However, you will more than likely have &quot;at least&quot; 2 spells in your discard which you must take in addition to the Sorreah&#39;s Dream, whether you like them or not, it&#39;s the rule!  The more spells you have in your discard, the better his options.  However, in the rare event that you have absolutely no spells in your discard, then yes, you may search your deck for the Sorreah&#39;s Dream and 2 more spells of your choice, but this scenario is highly unlikely.  Anyway, if they are available, Cataclysm or Shockwaves are your priority when choosing your starters.  If not, take a good look at the board and your hand, and take whatever you feel will help you most.  If you&#39;ve controlled the game up until this point, they should be on their last magi and you should be able to provide them w/ a devastating final blow.  First, you want to completely wipe the board of their creatures...ideally w/ Cataclysm...but if need be, Shockwave, Xyx Elder, Alaban, etc.  W/ their Creatures out of the way, their magi is defenseless.  This leaves you w/ several options w/ which to finish them.<br>
<br>
1st:  The single Dark Ayebaw in the deck is there just for this occasion and this occasion only.  So be sure to save it if drawn early on.  Play the Dark Ayebaw and use its Implode power on their magi and then discard your hand to deal &quot;2+the number of arderial cards discarded&quot; in damage to their magi.  In most cases, this should be more than enough to kill them.  <br>
<br>
2nd:  Play a Xyx and then use your Sorreah&#39;s Dream to copy its Shock power to deal 4 additional damage before using the Xyx itself, dealing a total of 8 damage to their magi.<br>
<br>
3rd:  Play the 2nd copy of Cloud Sceptre.  Having memorized the deck, you should be able to judge what cards you have left by analyzing your hand and your discard.  If you discover you have any Warrior&#39;s Boots left in the deck, you can use the Cloud Sceptre&#39;s Mindwinds power to discard your hand except for the Sorreah&#39;s Dream, and draw that many cards.  Didn&#39;t get it...?  Use the Sorreah&#39;s Dream to do it again.  W/ a Warrior&#39;s Boots in hand, you should be able to make short work of their defenseless magi.  This strategy allows you to get around the restriction of having to lose any Warrior&#39;s Boots in hand when using Cataclysm and becomes much more deadly when combined w/ an Ayebaw, which is a 5 energy base set Arderial creature that can attack twice!<br>
<br>
However, should your opponent be ahead, Sorreah will have a nice advantage in many situations and provide you w/ a fighting chance.  His Suppress effect will shut off the opposing magi&#39;s powers and effects, causing them to play the game on your terms.  W/ your superior skills you should be able to take anyone down in time!;)  Sorreah will have some trouble taking on magi such as Quilla that energize for 7 and have no powers or effects!:(  In this case, show no signs of intimidation and play your best...you&#39;d be surprised what you&#39;re capable of!<br>
<br>
FINAL NOTES:<br>
Sorreah&#39;s Dream is a wonderfull spell that can not only copy the great powers on your cards, but your opponent&#39;s as well!  Staring at a huge Giant Carrillion...?  Sorreah&#39;s Dream gives you a 6 energy Shockwave if you copy its Stomp power!  Copy a Greater Vaal&#39;s Immolate power for 5 energy and roll 2 die to hit anything you want, and even use Tryn&#39;s Refresh power for free to add 2 energy to 1 of your creatures for nothing!:)  Experiment w/ your own combinations, the possibilities are endless!<br>
<br>
Try and use the Cloud Narths and Pharans in combination w/ each other, as they can net you 3 free energy when discarded together.  Make a huge Flutter Yup and watch your opponent cry!:)<br>
<br>
Alaban&#39;s are a great way to deal w/ creatures that can&#39;t be discarded from play.  For 5 energy, they can return any creature in play to its owners hand and all the energy they paid for it is gone!  Use your Cloud Narths, Pharans, Lightnings and Shooting Star to pump them up when needed and Undream again and again!:)<br>
<br>
Hopefully, this has been a very helpfull and informative introduction to the ever versatile region of Arderial, which I&#39;m sure you will find yourself returning to time and time again.  <br>
I know I have!  Good Luck!:)<br>
<br>
Ryan<br>
